    • Normalization; creatinine and age

Data modelling

  • 1:1 Training- and validation-set split
  • Seperate/Multinomial logistic regression (glm)

  • Candidate 1: binary plasma CA19_9 (cutoff 37 U/ml)
  • Cand. 2 (Old panel): REG1A, LYVE1, TFF1; corrected for age and creatinine
  • Cand. 3 (without plasma): REG1B, LYVE1, TFF1; corrected for age and creatinine
  • Cand. 4 (PancRISK): REG1B, LYVE1, TFF1 and binary plasma CA19_9; corrected for age and creatinine

Discussion

  • Blood vs Urinary diagnosis classification :

  • 1) K-means based on urinary bio-markers slightly better than the one based on plasma_CA19_9

  • 2) Blood plasma shows importance in classification during the multinational logistic regression

  • 3) The complete model including blood and urinary markers achieves the best sensitivity and specificity

  • Possible explanation:

  • 1) Patients with malignant diagnosis should be subdivided into stages to improve the classification performance.

  • 2) Loss of 160 observations due to plasma_CA19_9 NA values

  • Further research aim:

  • Discovery of new urinary bio-markers could provide a non invasive diagnosis with better diagnosis accuracy
